           <p class="u-spacing-top-em u-spacing-bottom-em u-ls-n-05 u-lh-14">
            Audiomack continues moving music forward by fusing your favorite trap hits with a full orchestra. With violins in the cut, trap music never sounded better.
           </p>

             Watch Now

class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Falbum\u002Ftenientertainer\u002Fwondaland\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"352\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ftenientertainer\"\u003ETeni\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is the Minister of Enjoyment for a reason. The Nigerian singer-songwriter crafts music for having fun in life, becoming one of the leading women in Afrobeats over the past few years through tight songwriting and natural versatility, as heard on hit songs like “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ftenientertainer\u002Fsong\u002Fcase\"\u003ECase\u003C\u002Fa\u003E” and “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ftenientertainer\u002Fsong\u002Fbillionaire\"\u003EBillionaire\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.” \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ftenientertainer\u002Falbum\u002Fwondaland\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EWONDALAND\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, her official debut album, follows a Davido-featuring single (“\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ftenientertainer\u002Fsong\u002Ffor-you\"\u003EFOR YOU\u003C\u002Fa\u003E”) and delivers 17 tracks of bright, colorful Afropop for every mood.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"lana-del-rey-chemtrails-over-the-country-club\"\u003ELana Del Rey — \u003Cem\u003EChemtrails Over the Country Club\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor a decade, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Flanadelray\"\u003ELana Del Rey\u003C\u002Fa\u003E has honed her wistful, cinematic brand of Americana, culminating in her 2019 opus, \u003Cem\u003ENorman Fucking Rockwell!\u003C\u002Fem\u003E. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Flanadelray\u002Falbum\u002Fchemtrails-over-the-country-club\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EChemtrails Over the Country Club\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, her seventh album, is a more intimate affair than its predecessor, trading the coastline for more rural pastures and most of the sweeping grandeur for the romantic notion of small-town living. Lana may be ditching Calabasas for Lincoln, Nebraska, but the ballads still sound bigger than life.  \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"benny-the-butcher-harry-fraud-the-plugs-i-met-2\"\u003EBenny The Butcher &amp; Harry Fraud — \u003Cem\u003EThe Plugs I Met 2\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Falbum\u002Fbenny-the-butcher\u002Fthe-plugs-i-met-2\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"352\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf 2018’s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fbenny-the-butcher\u002Falbum\u002Ftana-talk-3\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETana Talk 3\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E announced \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fbenny-the-butcher\"\u003EBenny The Butcher\u003C\u002Fa\u003E as deserving of the praise his fellow \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fgriselda\"\u003EGriselda\u003C\u002Fa\u003E members \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fwestside-gunn\"\u003EWestside Gunn\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fconwaythemachine\"\u003EConway\u003C\u002Fa\u003E had garnered as burgeoning underground rap heroes, then 2019’s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fbenny-the-butcher\u002Falbum\u002Fthe-plugs-i-met\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EThe Plugs I Met\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E EP solidified the possibility he might actually be the crew’s breakout star, able to more than hold his own alongside \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fblackthought\"\u003EBlack Thought\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fpusha-t\"\u003EPusha-T\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fjadakiss\"\u003EJadakiss\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fbenny-the-butcher\u002Falbum\u002Fthe-plugs-i-met-2\"\u003Esequel\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, produced entirely by Harry Fraud, arrives five months after the blockbuster \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fbenny-the-butcher\u002Falbum\u002Fburden-of-proof\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBurden of Proof\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E \u003C\u002Fem\u003Eand four months after the artist was shot during a botched robbery attempt. Its sound and content are darker, more concerned with the comedown than the high. It’s another step forward for the Buffalo rapper. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"pink-siifu-fly-anakin-mokebreak-ep\"\u003EPink Siifu &amp; Fly Anakin — \u003Cem\u003E$mokebreak EP\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Falbum\u002Fflysiifu\u002Fsmokebreak-ep\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"352\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn November 2020, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fpinksiifu\"\u003EPink Siifu\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ffly-anakin\"\u003EFly Anakin\u003C\u002Fa\u003E opened up shop with \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fflysiifu\u002Falbum\u002Fflysiifus\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFlySiifu’s\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a collaborative album centered around a record store concept that showcased the natural chemistry between the two rappers and their lo-fi styles. \u003Cem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fflysiifu\u002Falbum\u002Fsmokebreak-ep\"\u003E$mokebreak\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, a follow-up EP that doubles as a deluxe version extension, lowers the stakes but matches the fun, collecting a bevy of other underground talents to lay down raps over hazy production. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"kota-the-friend-statik-selektah-to-kill-a-sunrise\"\u003EKOTA the Friend &amp; Statik Selektah — \u003Cem\u003ETo Kill a Sunrise\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Falbum\u002Fkotathefriend\u002Fto-kill-a-sunrise\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"352\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlending witty one-liners with honest introspection and a sunny, infectious disposition, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fkotathefriend\"\u003EKOTA the Friend\u003C\u002Fa\u003E has established himself as one of the biggest independent rap artists. For \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fkotathefriend\u002Falbum\u002Fto-kill-a-sunrise\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETo Kill a Sunrise\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, he teams up with veteran producer \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fstatikselektah\"\u003EStatik Selektah\u003C\u002Fa\u003E for 10 tracks of warm boom bap. The intergenerational pairing plays to both artists’ strengths, making for an easy but no less compelling listen.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","comment_id":"6054af4f2fae7d5acbee39e6","feature_image":"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Ftop-5-3.jpeg","featured":false,"created_at":"2021-03-19T10:03:59.000-04:00","updated_at":"2021-03-19T13:10:00.000-04:00","published_at":"2021-03-19T12:17:06.000-04:00","custom_excerpt":"Teni, Lana Del Rey, Benny The Butcher & Harry Fraud, Pink Siifu & Fly Anakin, and KOTA the Friend & Statik Selektah all have albums you need this week on Audiomack.","codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"custom_template":null,"canonical_url":null,"primary_author":null,"primary_tag":null,"primary_artist":null,"url":"https:\u002F\u002Fghost.audiomack.com\u002Fnew-albums-2021-3-19\u002F","page":false,"excerpt":"Teni, Lana Del Rey, Benny The Butcher & Harry Fraud, Pink Siifu & Fly Anakin, and KOTA the Friend & Statik Selektah all have albums you need this week on Audiomack.","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":"5 New Albums You Need to Hear This Week (3\u002F19)","meta_description":"Teni, Lana Del Rey, Benny The Butcher & Harry Fraud, Pink Siifu & Fly Anakin, and KOTA the Friend & Statik Selektah all have albums you need this week on Audiomack."},{"id":"60521f952fae7d5acbee35ef","uuid":"7f589e3d-6fcb-4f44-9a8f-73e80de04ce2","title":"Rubi Rose Wants to Go Harder","slug":"rubi-rose-interview","html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Frubi-rose\"\u003ERubi Rose\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is meticulous. She’s hyper-aware of how she perceives herself and the next phases of her career as a woman in rap. “I just record every single night,” she tells me over Google Meet. “I’m working with so many different producers, different artists. I’m just trying to get this sound right.”\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Frubi-rose\u002Fthe-truth\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDebuting formally as a rapper just three years ago, the 22-year-old intentionally leaked “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Frubi-rose\u002Fsong\u002Fon-top\"\u003EOn Top\u003C\u002Fa\u003E”: a loosie with her then-boyfriend Playboi Carti. Cringing at the song’s mention, Rose admits that both her gateway into rap and her short-lived DJ-career during her time at Georgia State University—under the moniker Rubiana—were “wack.” “I did like one set for A3C, and that was so bad,” she says. Though the criticism across social media was hard to read, she used it to fuel her love of writing and delivering bars.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHoning in on what felt like a larger-than-life, audacious approach to the mic, Rubi Rose found a social media breakthrough in “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fthee-rubi-rose\u002Fsong\u002Fbig-mouth\"\u003EBig Mouth\u003C\u002Fa\u003E,” released in 2019. While her early music exists in what she calls the “pussy rap” space, Rubi is adamant that her story will be told in multifaceted ways on future songs.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fthee-rubi-rose\u002Fbig-mouth\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERubi Rose’s hoarse and unnerving cadence garnered her attention from \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fcardi-b\"\u003ECardi B\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, who approached her—as well as \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fmulatto\"\u003EMulatto\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fsukihana\"\u003ESukihana\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and ROSALÍA—to star in the “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fcardi-b\u002Fsong\u002Fwap\"\u003EWAP\u003C\u002Fa\u003E” music video last year. It was a “dream come true” for Rose, who sampled a compliment from Cardi for the introduction to her recent mixtape, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Frubi-rose\u002Falbum\u002Ffor-the-streets\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFor The Streets\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, released in February.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFor The Streets\u003C\u002Fem\u003E flirts with the potential of Rubi Rose, the rapper. It’s packed with aspiration and tongue-in-cheek humor and demonstrates Rose’s wide-ranging ear for production. “I’m a huge lover of Latin American music, so I wanted to incorporate that,” she explains. While the project was a milestone in her career, Rubi Rose isn’t satisfied: “I just want to go harder in every capacity next time around.”\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Frubi-rose-vert.jpg\" class=\"kg-image\" alt\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EI know you’re focused on recording your next album and on telling “real” stories. What’s different about the process now?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI’m trying to get more personal. I want something to be able to relate to, not just the “rah rah rah, pussy talk.” What’s changed is my writing process and even my beat selections. I’m not doing all just drill or trap. I’m trying to get slower, more melodic selections to really rap on. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI just went through a breakup, and I moved to LA, and I’m growing as an artist, so there’s so much to talk about internally. I want girls to be empowered and confident and be reminded of their value. I want all of that to come through on the album too. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYou have a husky, distinct cadence that the likes of Cardi B have complimented. How did you find that part of your voice and exaggerate it?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhenever I get loud and get animated, I tap into the type of things I learned in Atlanta. The slang, the way some people talk, it’s now regular to me. I’m quite confident in the right settings in my personal life, so I guess this was always just natural to me. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Frubi-rose\u002Fintro-cardi-b-interlude\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYou’ve moved around a lot in your life, living in Switzerland for boarding school, for example. When did you move to Atlanta, and what were your initial impressions of the area?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMy mother, even from a young age, made sure me and my sisters were well-traveled. I feel like I have such an open mind and appreciation for different sorts of people. I came to Atlanta at a cool time because everything was buzzing around that 2013-14 period. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI’d moved from [Gwinnett County] where the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fmigos\"\u003EMigos\u003C\u002Fa\u003E are from, I was at high school there. [Migos] were getting popping and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fyoungthug\"\u003E[Young] Thug\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Frichhomiequan\"\u003ERich Homie Quan\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ffuture\"\u003EFuture\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. “Stoner” and “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fmigos\u002Fsong\u002Fversace-feat-drake\"\u003EVersace\u003C\u002Fa\u003E” had just come out too. It was good to witness it all.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Frubi-rose-vert-2.jpg\" class=\"kg-image\" alt\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYou recently released \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFor The Streets\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E, which is a hard-hitting and passionate debut mixtape. What fuels your ability to be so unapologetic throughout?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt’s really me and my real life. That aggression, to an extent, comes out there, or maybe it’s a part of who I want to be also. I’d say it just comes naturally for myself and my stories. I’d never say it was too crazy [in relation to struggling], but there’s been some tough times in college where I didn’t have as much as I wanted to. Experiences like that motivate me because it’s crazy to see where I am today.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Frubi-rose\u002Fwhole-lotta-liquor\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhich song was the most challenging for you to record?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProbably the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Frubi-rose\u002Fsong\u002Fwhole-lotta-liquor\"\u003Esong\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with Future and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fpartynextdoor\"\u003EPARTYNEXTDOOR\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. I still don’t like myself on it. It’s Party and Future—I didn’t deliver, and that’s okay. There’s always the next time. But I know that the verse didn’t meet my expectations.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeing included in Cardi B’s “WAP” cameos, and as one of the next generation of women in rap, do you see a progressing landscape for women?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt’s a really good time for us right now, for all of us. When men do remixes, we are now featured more. We’re really putting on for the ones after us. When the world opens up and we can do more shows, it will only get better.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYou’re beginning to record your debut album. Mentally, how different is the process for you?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI hear myself and want to see myself sounding a little bit different than where I’m currently at now. I don’t exactly think I’ve found the sound just yet. But I feel like I haven’t been making the best music because I’m not a night person and have been recording then. I’m a morning person. I need to change my routine. I’m also starting a writing camp soon.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Falbum\u002Frubi-rose\u002Ffor-the-streets\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"352\" scrollbars=\"no\" href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.instagram.com\u002Fdeangelophotos\u002F?hl=en\"\u003E@deangelophotos\u003C\u002Fa\u003E (blue) and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.instagram.com\u002Fstevengomillion\u002F?hl=en\"\u003ESteven Streets.'"},{"id":"605386752fae7d5acbee38ea","uuid":"d49518f0-44ab-45dd-a468-40b8d182a0b5","title":"Audiomack Partners With DistroKid to Enable Direct Distribution for Independent Artists","slug":"audiomack-partners-with-distrokid","html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAudiomack\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E has secured a partnership with \u003Cstrong\u003EDistroKid\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E, the world’s leading distributor of independent music, paving the way for more than 2 million artists to directly distribute their music to the platform. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pairing marks the first time Audiomack has agreed to an integrated partnership with a direct-to-artist music distributor like DistroKid. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E“At Audiomack we have built a reputation as an ally to emerging music creators and superstars alike,” said Audiomack CMO and Co-Founder \u003Cstrong\u003EDavid Ponte\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E in a statement about the partnership. “DistroKid releases an enormous amount of new music from emerging artists, so we’re thrilled to be able to work with them to make it easier than ever for artists to be on Audiomack and utilize powerful free tools like our creator dashboard. With this deal, we are giving even more artists the chance to be successful and discover devoted new fans on Audiomack.”\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDistroKid users can now connect to their Audiomack account and have their music distributed directly to their artist profile on Audiomack with just a click of a button. If a DistroKid user doesn’t have an existing Audiomack profile, they will have the ability to create one through this integration. The option will appear as an “Extras” when uploading their latest release.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E“Audiomack has become an influential platform for artists and music creators all over the world,” said DistroKid founder \u003Cstrong\u003EPhilip Kaplan\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E. “We're excited to make it super easy for the millions of artists who rely on DistroKid to seamlessly connect with Audiomack in a powerful &amp; convenient way.”\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStay tuned for a help guide on connecting your Audiomack account to your DistroKid account, allowing you to sync your uploads.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","comment_id":"605386752fae7d5acbee38ea","feature_image":"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002FAM-distrokid.jpg","featured":false,"created_at":"2021-03-18T12:57:25.000-04:00","updated_at":"2021-03-18T14:32:16.000-04:00","published_at":"2021-03-18T14:32:16.000-04:00","custom_excerpt":"Audiomack partners with DistroKid, paving the way for indie artists to establish a presence on the platform.","codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"custom_template":null,"canonical_url":null,"primary_author":null,"primary_tag":null,"primary_artist":null,"url":"https:\u002F\u002Fghost.audiomack.com\u002Faudiomack-partners-with-distrokid\u002F","page":false,"excerpt":"Audiomack partners with DistroKid, paving the way for indie artists to establish a presence on the platform.","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":"Audiomack Partners With DistroKid: Announcement","meta_description":"Audiomack partners with DistroKid, paving the way for indie artists to establish a presence on the platform."},{"id":"60521eb52fae7d5acbee35bf","uuid":"c2fa36dd-b12b-4916-bd7d-f86d20e0b071","title":"Tony Shhnow Is Matching Quality With Quantity","slug":"tony-shhnow-interview","html":"\u003Cp\u003EEverything about Atlanta’s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fsos-tony\"\u003ETony Shhnow\u003C\u002Fa\u003E screams poise. From rap lines that calmly reassure you that there are fresh blue strips on the way to his fluid release schedule, which echoes the urgency of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fliltunechi\"\u003ELil Wayne\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fgucci-mane\"\u003EGucci Mane\u003C\u002Fa\u003E’s most prolific years, Shhnow is a lyricist who rubs his hands together like Birdman as things fall into plan.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fsos-tony\u002Fcustom-made\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETony Shhnow has been rapping for five years, but things started to pick up for the 24-year-old within the last two in large part due to the evolution of his classic-trap sound. His collaborations with producer cashcache can be praised for this development. The beatsmith’s productions carry the zen of trap house yoga sessions, enabling Shhnow’s trigger-happy TED Talks delivered in the mellowest vibe possible. Songs like “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fsos-tony\u002Fsong\u002Fcustom-made\"\u003ECustom Made”\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fsos-tony\u002Fsong\u002Fhalf-time-show\"\u003EHALF TIME SHOW\u003C\u002Fa\u003E” could spin lawn pinwheels while Shhnow’s whispering makes you circle the speaker, eager to take in every word.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn early March, Shhnow put out his sixth project in the last year and his biggest yet, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fsos-tony\u002Falbum\u002Fdis-should-hold-u-over-2\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDis Should Hold U Over 2\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. His carefully calculated release style is inspired by Gucci Mane’s legendary late 2000s run, yet Shhnow nearly didn’t release his latest full-length. “I didn’t want to give it to the folks immediately because I didn’t want to burn out the sound,” he says. This awareness, and an ever-present focus on blending a hustler’s mentality with quality music, is helping to set up Tony Shhnow for the long-term.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Ftony-shhnow-vert-2.jpeg\" class=\"kg-image\" alt\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowing up, you wanted to be a basketball player. That changed in sixth grade when you wanted to start rapping. What happened?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELil Wayne’s \u003Cem\u003ENo Ceilings\u003C\u002Fem\u003E mixtape had just come out, and my friend Brandon was super into it. I wasn’t too heavy into it like that. I really wasn’t into rap music too much, period—I was just discovering it. And Brandon played basketball too, and, coincidentally, he didn’t make the team like I didn’t. We would go home and play Lil Wayne’s music while playing\u003Cem\u003E Call of Duty\u003C\u002Fem\u003E and shit like that. Eventually, that turned into us cutting on beats and Brandon starting to rap over them. I always thought that was cool. And he was like, “Well, why don’t you try it?” That just led me in to start rapping.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhen did you start releasing your own music?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI used to rap with people in the neighborhood and appear on their songs before I took it super seriously. They’d have spots open on their songs, and I’d hop on. But officially becoming Tony Shhnow didn’t come until 2014 when I met producer SenseiATL that December. I had a song that was kind of going viral related to \u003Cem\u003ENBA 2K\u003C\u002Fem\u003E—a YouTuber would use it in his tutorial videos. When I met SenseiATL, that’s when it turned into making original music, like something from my own brain, nobody around influencing. It wasn’t no YouTube beat; it was official music.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhat do you remember of making music during your early times?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere was this dude from my school who was in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fsoulja-boy\"\u003ESoulja Boy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E’s SODMG, and he let me come to the studio and record with him. I was getting into based music. I had gone through the Lil Wayne era in middle school, but I was just starting to find the internet music in high school—the Soulja Boys, the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Flilbthebasedgod\"\u003ELil B\u003C\u002Fa\u003Es, the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Friff-raff\"\u003ERiff Raff\u003C\u002Fa\u003Es, the cooking music. So for that dude to be right there and embrace me, that shit was pretty cool. That shit put a battery in my back. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI’m saying, as far as people from my city being able to make it or being on a bigger platform. Because most niggas come from just Atlanta. Most niggas come from the South Side or the West Side. You don’t see a lot of Cobb or Marietta people specifically just being able to break that platform and go mainstream.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fsos-tony\u002Fhalf-time-show\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne thing you’re known for is your consistency when it comes to releasing music. What’s your secret?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMy mom always told me to go hard coming up. She just instilled a work ethic in me early on. She was trying to make me get a job at 15. So, in life, period, just working, I’m instilled with that. And then when it comes to music, I look at rappers like Lil Wayne and Gucci and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fwakaflockaflame\"\u003EWaka [Flocka]\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and artists that just drop bodies of work that make you become hooked to the music.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce you get on there, you can’t stop listening to them. Now I gotta keep hearing this voice and what he has to say, so that’s part of what that is. Quality, I think, comes from my drive. I don’t want to be no rapper that’s just in this shit for a year and a half and then be out of here. I’ve watched the game for a minute. I noticed that quality wins every time. Although hustle outweighs talent, you can’t really beat talent at the end of the day if they combine that. There ain’t nobody stopping you if you got both.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHow long have you been engineering and mixing your own songs?  \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI’ve kind of always done that. Once I learned from working with SenseiATL and took it to trying to work on my own, that’s when I began to engineer myself. Even when I was recording with both of them and SOD, I was literally just watching niggas play shit—how they toyed with sounds, how much they turned them up, what number to play with, what to click on the keyboard. Even when they were making beats, I’m watching them do so. I’m like a spy in the studio.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHow often do you make your own beats?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI do sometimes, but I don’t really be on them like that because I’m so spontaneous. When I hear a beat, I don’t want to hear that bitch for more than 30 seconds without rapping on it. As soon as I hear it, I got to rap on that bitch, right then and there. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EI also wanted to ask you about cashcache. What’s it like working with him? You guys have developed your own sound that just continues to click with each release. \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI really enjoy working with him. He’s one of my favorite producers. We normally work through the internet, but when we work in person, it’s always cool. I like his energy. He makes me feel like I’m the greatest rapper alive. I’ll just be talking regularly; he comes over there and makes me feel good about the bars, so that shit makes me talk extra crazy shit on the next record.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWho inspires you the most right now?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI’ve been trying to channel Wayne’s energy in general because I’ve looked at his story, and he was the little guy that no one necessarily was looking at. Nobody thought he would go on to become the greatest rapper in the whole world. They didn’t realize this nigga’s going to take the whole world over. They’re thinking bro’s going to come in here and do a little, drop a couple of records here and there. That’s how I feel about myself. I’ve been feeling like I was looked over for a long time; nobody was expecting me to drop classics or nothing like that. Lil Wayne is the goal. I’m trying to be the greatest.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Falbum\u002Fsos-tony\u002Fdis-should-hold-u-over-2\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"352\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPhotos by Zoomanloki (main) and Reggie Moore.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","comment_id":"60521eb52fae7d5acbee35bf","feature_image":"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Ftony-shhnow-horiz.jpeg","featured":false,"created_at":"2021-03-17T11:22:29.000-04:00","updated_at":"2021-03-19T13:05:51.000-04:00","published_at":"2021-03-18T10:56:56.000-04:00","custom_excerpt":"The Atlanta rapper's strategy is taking inspiration from Lil Wayne and Gucci Mane's prolific runs.","codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"custom_template":null,"canonical_url":null,"primary_author":null,"primary_tag":null,"primary_artist":null,"url":"https:\u002F\u002Fghost.audiomack.com\u002Ftony-shhnow-interview\u002F","page":false,"excerpt":"The Atlanta rapper's strategy is taking inspiration from Lil Wayne and Gucci Mane's prolific runs.","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":"Tony Shhnow Interview: Matching Quality & Quantity","meta_description":"Atlanta rapper Tony Shhnow speaks with Audiomack about his career, idols, and matching quality with quantity."},{"id":"6051db662fae7d5acbee3594","uuid":"d6f21481-fe28-4271-bea9-ddea0e8d0dac","title":"Yung Baby Tate Is #UpNow","slug":"yung-baby-tate-is-upnow","html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EWhat’s up next in culture is #UpNow on Audiomack. Our emerging artist program is dedicated to spotlighting and promoting the next generation of global music superstars.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGeorgia rapper and singer \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fyungbabytate\"\u003EYung Baby Tate\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is Audiomack’s latest #UpNow artist.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAffirmation queen Yung Baby Tate is a multi-hyphenate phenomenon. Her rapping, singing, producing, and dancing exists in a special lane meant to create space for Black girls to feel themselves. From 2019’s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fyungbabytate\u002Falbum\u002Fgirls\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGIRLS\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, with a song for every woman, to 2020’s viral “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fyungbabytate\u002Fsong\u002Fi-am\"\u003EI Am\u003C\u002Fa\u003E,” featuring \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fflo-milli\"\u003EFlo Milli\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, Yung Baby Tate’s music is an explosion of color and charisma. Tate’s most recent release, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fyungbabytate\u002Falbum\u002Fafter-the-rain\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAfter the Rain\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, continues the track record of excellence she first established in 2015 with \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fyungbabytate\u002Falbum\u002Froygbiv\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EROYGBIV\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. “\u003Cem\u003EYou can’t outdo the doer, okay?\u003C\u002Fem\u003E” she boasts on “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fyungbabytate\u002Fsong\u002Frainbow-cadillac\"\u003ERainbow Cadillac\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.” \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrom a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fworld\u002Fpost\u002Fyung-baby-tate-interview\"\u003Efeature interview on Audiomack World\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fworld\u002Fpost\u002Flisten-to-audiomack---leaders-of-the-new-cool-s-official-sxsw-showcase-playlist\"\u003Eperforming\u003C\u002Fa\u003E at our Leaders of the New Cool SXSW showcase in 2019, Yung Baby Tate has long been an Audiomack favorite, and has racked up millions of streams and a loyal fanbase on the platform.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E“It’s definitely an honor because I feel like I’ve been putting a lot of work in and for that to be recognized feels really good,” Tate said in regards to her #UpNow selection. “I think I’ve always been on the rise, but for everyone to kind of understand and see this moment as I do for myself, it’s really just affirming. So great.” \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fplaylist\u002Faudiomack\u002Fupnow\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"352\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYung Baby Tate is the cover artist of Audiomack’s official #UpNow playlist. Stay tuned for an exclusive interview with the #UpNow artist, coming next week.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","comment_id":"6051db662fae7d5acbee3594","feature_image":"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002F-UpNow_world.png","featured":false,"created_at":"2021-03-17T06:35:18.000-04:00","updated_at":"2021-03-17T12:59:07.000-04:00","published_at":"2021-03-17T12:59:07.000-04:00","custom_excerpt":"Affirmation queen Yung Baby Tate is a multi-hyphenate phenomenon, and our latest #UpNow artist.","codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"custom_template":null,"canonical_url":null,"primary_author":null,"primary_tag":null,"primary_artist":null,"url":"https:\u002F\u002Fghost.audiomack.com\u002Fyung-baby-tate-is-upnow\u002F","page":false,"excerpt":"Affirmation queen Yung Baby Tate is a multi-hyphenate phenomenon, and our latest #UpNow artist.","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":"Yung Baby Tate Is #UpNow: Announcement","meta_description":"Affirmation queen Yung Baby Tate is a multi-hyphenate phenomenon, and the latest Audiomack #UpNow artist."},{"id":"6051da762fae7d5acbee3565","uuid":"f6bae706-ed52-44c4-9ee0-ca0b06c14afb","title":"Step Into MohBad’s Light","slug":"mohbad-interview","html":"\u003Cp\u003EOf all the music coming out of Lagos right now, none is as precise and truthful as the songs of angst and hedonism springing out of the city’s mainland. In these places where lives are pressed against the edges of survival, and real life can turn into a nightmare in an instant, music is an escape.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fmohbad\u002Fwav-mohbad-sorry\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fmohbad\"\u003EMohBad\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, born Ilerioluwa Oladimeji Aloba, knows this and pays homage to that knowledge in his music. “I think it is important to note that to be from and on the streets, it takes a lot,” he tells me over the phone. “You have to be rugged with your words and aspects of your life sometimes.”\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlways passionate about music, MohBad started taking his career seriously two years ago with the viral release of “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fmohbad\u002Fsong\u002Fronaldo-naijaloadedcomng\"\u003ERonaldo\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.” Since then, he’s been dropping consistently, telling stories of his harrowed experiences as a young man in Nigeria.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThose experiences and his unabashed embrace of his community in Ikorodu via interpolated traditional Yoruba melodies and sharp-witted hood lingo made MohBad’s debut project, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fmohbad\u002Falbum\u002Flight-the-ep\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELight\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, released in December 2020, a fascinating experience in meshing the boisterous with the sentimental. “I just wanted people to know more about me and what I’m about,” he says. Much of the project is a voyage into the mind of the 24-year-old, exploring the essence, and cost, of depression, sex, and drugs over vibrant beats in nexus with several guests like \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fdavido\"\u003EDavido\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fnaira-marley\"\u003ENaira Marley\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fmohbad\u002Fonce-debe\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile MohBad acknowledges this part of his origin, he is not afraid to admit he is trying to step into a new light as his artistic and personal evolution continues. “You can see it from the cover too: the idea was me moving away from the darkness into that light and also sharing the light with my fans too.”\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhen did you know music was what you wanted to do professionally?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI’ve been doing music for as long as I can remember, but I took it seriously about three years ago, and since then, I’ve been dropping music consistently.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E“Ronaldo” was my first song that went viral. It just became a big deal in my hood, Ikorodu, and neighboring communities. Seeing people reacting to the song gave me a boost to keep at music and made me realize it was something I could do for a living. I started posting freestyles more frequently on Instagram and other platforms ‘til Naira Marley noticed me and signed me to Marlian Music.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Fmohbad-vert.jpeg\" class=\"kg-image\" alt\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYou signed your deal in December 2019. How has the transition been from being an independent artist?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt’s been an entirely new experience for me because I’m learning to work within a label structure. It’s not something I knew about as an independent musician. But I’m also making new experiences and enjoying the ride as much as I can. On the other hand, I also try to keep working and focus on giving out the best I can.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYour debut EP is named \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELight\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E. What is the significance of that title for you?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt’s just an extension of who I am. Everyone keeps calling me Imole (Light), and I wanted my debut project to be an actual breakthrough to that light. You can see it from the cover, too: the idea was me moving away from the darkness into that light and also sharing the light with my fans too.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fmohbad\u002Fmarlians-anthem\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIs there a song on the project that is most memorable for you?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt has to be “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fmohbad\u002Fsong\u002Fmarlians-anthem\"\u003EMarlians Anthem\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.” I love the energy of the song. It was one of those times when I didn’t go into the studio with a mindset of what I wanted to say; I was just in the mood and had \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Frexxiepondabeat\"\u003ERexxie\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with me. He played a beat for me, and the first words that came out were the opener. It was so pure because that was exactly how I was feeling at the moment, and I just translated it musically.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnother thing that struck me about \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELight\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E was how biographical it feels. How important was it to tell your life’s story with the project?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat’s my life right there. The EP is everything about how my life has been up to this moment. From the beginning to the end of the project. As much as I wanted to bring people into the light, I wanted them to know about my life and the things I’ve faced to get to where I am right now. And I feel like since the project dropped, a lot more people understand who MohBad is—or at least, they have a better understanding.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Fmohbad-vert-2.jpeg\" class=\"kg-image\" alt\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOn the inverse, what’s something you still feel people don’t understand about MohBad?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere’s still a lot of people who just don’t know, but I’ll talk about it from a musical sense. A lot of people think MohBad is just a rapper, but I don’t agree with that because there’s still so much I’m discovering about myself. I can’t even call myself a rapper or a singer; I’d just say I’m an artist. In my mind, I can do anything, and that’s why the EP was so important because I was able to show the range of my talent.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlong with \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fzinoleesky\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZinoleesky\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E and \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fbella-shmurda\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBella Shmurda\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E, you’re bringing the stories of the hoods of Lagos to mainstream consciousness. How does it feel to be achieving this?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMan, it makes me feel so good because this is all I worked for, all I prayed for. I started this journey because I believed we could get here, and I don’t think we’re done because we keep working hard and pushing each other to get better. At the same time, I’m grateful for the love from the street because they show up for me every time, and that’s great.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Frexxiepondabeat\u002Fko-po-ke\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYou ended the year with a hit single, “\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Frexxiepondabeat\u002Fsong\u002Fko-po-ke\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKPK\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E,” that you made with Rexxie. How did it happen?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E“KPK” was recorded after I’d finished work on my EP. I was still figuring out a release schedule for the project, but I posted a snippet of the song on Instagram, and people kept reaching out for it. I recorded the song in 10 minutes at Rexxie’s place; that’s why there’s no verse on it, just the ad-libs. We were at Rexxie’s to add back-up vocals to “Marlians Anthem,” and after we did that, I told him I wanted to work on any material he had. It was around 3 a.m., so I just wanted to drop some vocals and continue working on the song later in the day, but when I heard the song later, I knew I didn’t have to add anything. Rexxie also did crazy work with the production.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAre you conscious of your growing influence on a younger generation of fans?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI really care about my younger fans, but I’m also trying to be truthful to myself as much as possible. As an artist, I just have to say these things in my songs sometimes because that’s my reality. But I also have songs that my younger fans can listen to without any restrictions, that a family can listen to together. I think it is important to note that to be from and on the streets, it takes a lot. You have to be rugged with your words and aspects of your life sometimes, and this is me just reflecting that.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Falbum\u002Fmohbad\u002Flight-the-ep\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"352\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPhotos by 22.Jumpstr (main) and Uzii.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","comment_id":"6051da762fae7d5acbee3565","feature_image":"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Fmohbad-horiz.jpeg","featured":false,"created_at":"2021-03-17T06:31:18.000-04:00","updated_at":"2021-03-18T15:21:36.000-04:00","published_at":"2021-03-17T10:29:00.000-04:00","custom_excerpt":"MohBad has won over the streets, telling stories of his harrowed experiences as a young man in Nigeria.","codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"custom_template":null,"canonical_url":null,"primary_author":null,"primary_tag":null,"primary_artist":null,"url":"https:\u002F\u002Fghost.audiomack.com\u002Fmohbad-interview\u002F","page":false,"excerpt":"MohBad has won over the streets, telling stories of his harrowed experiences as a young man in Nigeria.","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":"MohBad Interview: Nigeria, Community & 'Light'","meta_description":"Nigeria's MohBad speaks with Audiomack about his roots, putting on for his community, and his latest project, 'Light.'"},{"id":"6050897e2fae7d5acbee3507","uuid":"2250b06e-d2b9-4de4-bf82-309176fa4b66","title":"Abby Jasmine Is Your Favorite Cousin","slug":"abby-jasmine-interview","html":"\u003Cp\u003ENew York’s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fabby-jasmine\"\u003EAbby Jasmine\u003C\u002Fa\u003E was born to be a musician. Coming from a musical family, where her father played damn near every instrument and both parents supported her pursuit of the arts, it was only a matter of time until she forged her own way as a rapper-singer. Debuting in 2018 with \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fabby-jasmine\u002Falbum\u002Ftrap-mom\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETRAP MOM\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and releasing \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fabby-jasmine\u002Falbum\u002Fwho-cares\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EWho Cares?\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E along with an R&amp;B-infused \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fabby-jasmine\u002Falbum\u002Fwho-cares-deluxe\"\u003Edeluxe\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in 2020, Abby Jasmine weaves between hip-hop and R&amp;B with ease.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fabby-jasmine\u002Fon-god\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbby Jasmine is also positively hilarious. She got her start in the public eye as a Vine star, and though she could do without the constant reminders, her bubbly persona makes the warmth in her music all the more exciting. At 18, Jasmine finally decided music was the only way forward for her, spurred on by a desire to live life outside of the norms society lays out for people.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeing in the public eye since 16 has allowed Abby Jasmine to embrace her success. Part of her gets anxious when she realizes swarms of people have the ability to comment on her daily life, but messages from her fans keep her going, and more importantly, give her purpose. Abby Jasmine does it for the people.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhen did you realize it was music or bust for you?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI never could see myself working a regular job. When I was 12, I was always thinking about… I used to hold concerts in my room, lip-syncing Hilary Duff songs! I always knew I wanted to entertain and do something other than the traditional work thing. Of course, I had times like, “Fuck it, let me work at this call center job,” but keeping jobs? Not for me. I would get fired from every job. I was like, “Let me do this music.” That was around 18. There wasn’t really anything left for me. I tried to go to college and wasn’t feeling it. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Fabby-jasmine-vert-3.jpg\" class=\"kg-image\" alt\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevel with me: How tired are you of being asked about Vine?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOh my God! You are the first person [who asked] if I’m tired of hearing that question, so I appreciate you. I’m a little conflicted on it. I’m obviously tired of answering the question, just because Vine was a turning point for me as far as me acquiring my platform, but as far as my life now? I don’t really care to talk about the Vine days. Listen, I was bored, depressed, in my mom’s crib, 16, making videos. The followers and the numbers didn’t register with me until \u003Cem\u003Eyears\u003C\u002Fem\u003E later. Vine does not define who I am. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen people try to point out the fact I was on Vine before talking about my music, I’m sure people who interview me have no bad intentions, but to me, it feels like my music’s being downplayed. “She’s on Vine, now she makes music.” No! There’s so much that happened in between that.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThere’s so much more to you, obviously.\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI’m \u003Cem\u003Ecomplex\u003C\u002Fem\u003E!\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fabby-jasmine\u002F06-no-hook-explicit-sing-master\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhat’s the most misunderstood thing about you?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA lot of people, based off my music, think I—how do I phrase this? They think I have a lot of relationship issues. Of course, I’ve gone through those things, but when I’m singing, I’m not \u003Cem\u003Ecurrently\u003C\u002Fem\u003E going through it. I have a boyfriend, we’ve been together for three years, he’s great. A lot of people hit me up like, “Yo! Why you talking about him like that?” I’m not talking about \u003Cem\u003Ehim\u003C\u002Fem\u003E. I don’t really have those problems anymore, but I’m able to bring myself back into that place. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIs it weird when people who don’t know you comment on your life based on your art?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYes! People want to connect with music on a deeper level than just how they interpret it. So, them hitting me up, it kind of ruins the fun, sometimes. Create your own meaning out of a song. If I tell you, what if you’re underwhelmed? \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Fabby-jasmine-vert.jpg\" class=\"kg-image\" alt\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversely, what’s your favorite part of having a fan reach out?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI don’t really like the word “fans”; I be calling them my cousins. I grew up on the internet, and these people have seen me since I was 16. They love how authentic I am, and that inspires people to be their authentic selves. If I can do that for just one person, that’s cool to me. Sometimes, I’ll be like, “Damn… Am I good at this? Do people fuck with me?” Then I’ll get the message, “Abby, please don’t stop what you’re doing!” That’s the type of stuff that makes me keep going.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E“\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fabby-jasmine\u002Fsong\u002F06-no-hook-explicit-sing-master\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo Hook\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E” was one of your breakout records, and you’ve had other breakout moments. Is there a part of you that’s scared of your own success?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA part of me is kind of embracing it because people have been watching me since I was 16. So I’m used to the public eye, but a large part of me… I’m a real private person. I don’t like the internet in my business. When I see tabloids and stuff like that, that shit gives me anxiety. I don’t want thousands of people chiming in on my everyday life.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe Sweat","slug":"audiomack-womens-history-month-donations","html":"\u003Cp\u003EAudiomack continues to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fworld\u002Fpost\u002Faudiomack-celebrates-womens-history-month\"\u003Ecelebrate Women’s History Month\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with two donations of $2,000 each to women-led and woman-supporting organizations \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.girlswholisten.org\u002F\"\u003EGirls Who Listen\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fprettygirlssweat.com\u002F\"\u003EPretty Girls Sweat\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGirls Who Listen is a Black woman-owned non-profit dedicated to supporting future female creatives and executives in the music industry. Throughout the year, Girls Who Listen hosts a series of events such as panels, mingling mixers, songwriting sessions, and compiles an internal networking database for upcoming artists and media professionals who aim to learn more about the music industry.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPretty Girls Sweat is a Black female-owned brand founded in 2011 and headquartered in Atlanta, GA. This wellness company develops events, content, and products designed to make fitness fun, affordable, and accessible to all women.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E“The journey has been long and hard since 2011 when we vowed to develop young leaders through fitness,” said Pretty Girls Sweat Founder Aeshia DeVore Branch in response to the donation. “Monetary support coupled with awareness from Audiomack helps us continue to provide the most digestible health education in communities that don't have access. Like Audiomack, we value the importance of providing a platform for youth to make positive life choices. While the social music site empowers creatives through music, we uplift women who use music as a vehicle to improve their physical and mental health.”\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E“We have been very fortunate to reach our community through the digital space,” says Girls Who Listen CEO and Founder Kadijat Salawudeen. “However, COVID-19 has affected our plans to conduct in-person events. We’ve had to cancel songwriting sessions, where down payments on venues and event supplies were no longer needed. However, with the assistance of Audiomack’s donation, we'll be able to allocate some of the lost capital into our scholarship fund for students. We'd also like to invest in our programming budget, educational panels, workshops, and informational seminars with music companies and executives.”\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E“Like Girls Who Listen, Audiomack is constantly finding ways to give back, while supporting the future of the music industry,” adds Salawudeen. “We couldn't have been more grateful for this opportunity!”\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese donations come on the heels of Audiomack supporting the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fworld\u002Fpost\u002Faudiomack-nbcc-donation\"\u003Epartnering with the NBCC\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","comment_id":"604f5cea2fae7d5acbee34d6","feature_image":"https:\u002F\u002Fassets.audiomack.com\u002F_am-blog\u002F2021\u002F03\u002Fthumbs-AM-GWL_PGS-16x9.jpg","featured":false,"created_at":"2021-03-15T09:11:06.000-04:00","updated_at":"2021-03-15T12:57:33.000-04:00","published_at":"2021-03-15T11:46:53.000-04:00","custom_excerpt":"Audiomack 54","slug":"lo-fi-rap-snack-pack-2021-3-15","html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELo-fi rap embraces imperfection. Artists and producers utilize unmixed vocals, distorted drums, and tape hiss for their practical and aesthetic beauty. From RZA and Dilla to Earl Sweatshirt and Roc Marciano, the lo-fi scene is as rewarding and overwhelming a subgenre as any currently existing in rap. Welcome to the Lo-Fi Rap Snack Pack, a weekly column where we highlight four songs across the lo-fi spectrum. Listen to \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fcinemasai\u002Fplaylist\u002Flo-fi-snack-pack\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003Ethe Lo-Fi Snack Pack playlist\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E for these selections and more.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"wavy-bagels-force-\"\u003EWavy Bagels — “Force” \u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fwavy_bagels\u002Fforce\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EQueens rapper-producer \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fwavy_bagels\"\u003EWavy Bagels\u003C\u002Fa\u003E doesn’t rap often, so any time he picks up the mic is a special occasion. Ironically, his latest single, “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fwavy_bagels\u002Fsong\u002Fforce\"\u003EForce\u003C\u002Fa\u003E,” is about as casual as it gets. Slinky piano keys and drums propel the song while Bagels raps like he’s strolling to the bodega on a weekend morning. Bagels compares himself to R&amp;B singer Ruben Studdard before reminding listeners they aren’t entitled to anyone’s time. It’s a message as blunt as it is thoughtful, a perfect reflection of the music surrounding “Force.” \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"rubychocha-body-call-\"\u003ERubychocha — “Body Call” \u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Falex-ruby\u002Fbody-call\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical connection is something rapper-producer \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Falex-ruby\"\u003ERubychocha\u003C\u002Fa\u003E won’t ever take for granted again. His latest self-produced single, “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Falex-ruby\u002Fsong\u002Fbody-call\"\u003EBody Call\u003C\u002Fa\u003E,” is a quick trip through a hookup he feels could potentially turn into something more. The song is backed by a smooth soul sample and crisp kickdrums perfectly suited to the swelling awkwardness of potential new love. It’s unclear whether the vibe will last past the present night, but the feeling, like “Body Call” itself, lingers in the brain long after. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"melvin-alex-pure-joy-\"\u003EMelvin Alex — “Pure Joy” \u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Fmelvinalexbeats\u002Fpure-joy\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENew York producer \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fmelvinalexbeats\"\u003EMelvin Alex\u003C\u002Fa\u003E has a good ear for a sample. His latest single, “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fmelvinalexbeats\u002Fsong\u002Fpure-joy\"\u003EPure Joy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E,” is built around a piano sample that rises and falls on flitty fingers, creating an atmosphere reminiscent of jazz lounges of the early 1930s. It represents a specific kind of joy unstuck in time, one defined by a night out with good friends, wine, and cheese dominated by the swirling sounds of live piano.   \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Ch2 id=\"trck-night-drive-\"\u003ETrck. — “Night Drive” \u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe src=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Fembed\u002Fsong\u002Ftrckmusic\u002Fnight-drive\" scrolling=\"no\" width=\"649\" height=\"252\" scrollbars=\"no\" frameborder=\"0\"\u003E\u003C\u002Fiframe\u003E\u003C\u002Ffigure\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDriving at night can either be intense or relaxing, depending on the kind of music you’ve got playing when you touch road. When I listen to producer \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ftrckmusic\"\u003ETrck.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E’s “\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ftrckmusic\u002Fsong\u002Fnight-drive\"\u003ENight Drive\u003C\u002Fa\u003E,” a song from his latest project, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Faudiomack.com\u002Ftrckmusic\u002Falbum\u002Ftranquilize\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETranquilize\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003EI get a clear picture of what the act of night driving means to him. Synths twinkle on the horizon from a drop-top whip while drums and a wailing saxophone keep things grounded to Earth. “Night Drive” soundtracks the kind of trip I’d relish after a hard day at work, a beat to lose your mind in until reality and imagination blur together into one.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\"kg-card kg-embed-card\"\u003E\u003Ciframe
